<article>
    <h1>Tips for festive cel&#xAD;e&#xAD;bra&#xAD;tions</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201227/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-27"><time>2020-12-27</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>• Pre­pare just enough: Make a shop­ping list, buy only what you need, and cater for be­tween 10 and 15 per cent fewer than the num­ber of ex­pected guests.</p>
    <p>• Think be­fore you give: Pick food gifts that you know the re­cip­i­ent would en­joy, but avoid get­ting highly per­ish­able items such as fruit and dairy prod­ucts.</p>
    <p>• Go small: Peo­ple usu­ally pre­fer drink­ing and so­cial­is­ing to eat­ing a heavy meal dur­ing this festive sea­son, so pro­vide smaller plates to re­duce the amount of food left on them.</p>
    <p>• Freeze your left­overs in small por­tions: Di­vide left­overs into smaller por­tions and pack them into la­belled air­tight con­tain­ers be­fore freez­ing them. This makes foods freeze faster and re­duces the need to thaw more than you need. You can also save some cash when you have them for lunch at work.</p>
    <p>• Give away ex­cess food from your ham­per. You are not go­ing to need ev­ery­thing in the ham­per you have re­ceived, so why not share – or better still, do­nate the ex­cess non-per­ish­ables?</p>

